I was asked to submit a list of some of the questions my recent guest has asked me on social media, which is a good thing since I don't have to answer them in person, because I get asked this way all the time. A lot of times it turns out to be more fun than it appears at first glance, like "Do you take your dog to work when you're not home?" or "What's the deal with you and your husband?" or "What do you do with all of the pet peeves you get?"

My answer is probably a combination of everything that's best for me (unless I can't see you or even communicate with you), but I think at least a few of these would apply to people who write "I've done this before" posts for a living. In fact, it's my hope that the answer you find below might help you deal with some of the same questions that our guest did:

1. What is your pet peeve?

In my first article on this, I tried to outline four main pet peeves I've come across in my job:

Laying around in a pile of litter boxes.

Using toilet paper, or toilet paper and sanitary napkins.

Pumping water in the dishwasher.

Pumping up your dog's leg every once in a while.

The good news is that once you figure out the pet peeves you have, there's not a whole lot of things you can do about it. They're probably better left behind as part of the baggage you toss out into the garbage. So what does one do when his or her job involves putting down a dog? Well, this list is, frankly, pretty easy to find, even if it's not the "most" useful:

1. Talk to people who use the toilets

