A letter from U.S. Airways, the Nation's leading airline, expressing its support for the CFPB reform bill was sent to my office by the president of the National Association of Flight Attendants and myself.  I want to quote from the letter: ``Our experience on the CFPB since its inception has been very positive. With the CFPB providing the best value in our marketplace, we welcome these new reforms and look forward to continuing to work with the CFPB to ensure that all of our members have a fair playing field to play in the marketplace.''  For the past 10 months the CFPB has been negotiating for reform with the airline industry, but despite this process, industry interest has been frustrated. Now, the airlines have made clear they are willing to continue to negotiate the reforms without fear of being forced to pay back the money owed to them for the unfair practices that took place under the original CFPB's initial efforts.  Let me also say that I support the efforts of my colleague from Illinois, the chairman of the Small Business Committee, Senator Kirk, who has done an outstanding job working with the airlines in this effort. I know the airlines will continue to take the necessary steps to correct these unfair practices and they will continue to work closely with the CFPB to assure our stakeholders that the reforms are fair and that they will be transparent to all sides. We have said it, and we are taking them up on that.  This is not about one CEO versus another. This is about all the stakeholders, all the employees, and all of the customers in this country being treated fairly and in a fair way.  I hope my colleagues on the other side of the aisle will be able to come together and work with us in a bipartisan way to make this a reality, to allow the airlines to negotiate the reforms without fear of losing the money they have made since we left the CFPB, and to continue this fight until they bring us an honest, equitable and just agreement.  
