I rise today to oppose the bill, H.R. 2921, the Nuclear Waste Disposal Reform Act of 1995. I oppose this bill because it represents an unprecedented intrusion by Congress into the power of the States to determine the appropriate disposal of spent nuclear fuel in a State by State. This is not a well-intended and safe legislation. I strongly disagree with the bill's underlying intent, which is to make sure that the disposal of spent nuclear fuel in the United States is safe and environmentally sound.  First of all, let me be very clear. I believe we should keep the spent fuel rods at Yucca Mountain. I will vote for that because I believe the technology there is now and the nuclear waste is there, and the reactor itself is there. But I will vote no on this bill, because the people in my State want to have their own idea. I represent a State that is concerned with the environment and the environment and the health of its citizens. It is absolutely important that we, as Congress, have the ability to ensure the disposal of spent fuel in a safe and responsible manner.  Second, I am very supportive of the nuclear waste repository concept, which is the only way we can ensure that we can properly dispose of the spent fuel rods at Yucca Mountain. Nuclear waste disposal is one of the most cost-effective methods of disposing nuclear waste, but I believe we must also, in my opinion, consider the cost-effectiveness as well. But at the same time, we need to make sure that we do the most cost-effective way. That is what this bill does.  Let me explain what this bill is all about. This bill is an unprecedented intrusion into State power by the Federal Government. If you read the bill in its entirety, it does not say there will be any public hearing. It says if you feel that the State needs that extra money to carry out this program, there is a mechanism by which that money can be spent.  I find this a somewhat shocking statement to make, given what the American people expect us to do every day. You talk about the American people being given a free vote on this, but the Constitution grants the States the responsibility to pass budgets and to vote in elections, not to have this kind of mandate placed on them by a new bill.  Now, when we talk about this bill, what I am suggesting is we look at where is the money being spent. I think we have to ask, why do we want to mandate that we have
